---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from 'astrowind:config';

const crumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', href: '/' },
  { name: 'R&D Center', href: '/randdcenter' },
  { name: 'Fabric Sample & Prototype Workshop' },
];

const metadata = {
  title: `Fabric Sample & Prototype Workshop — Custom Fabric Sampling & Small Batch Production | ${SITE.name}`,
  description: `From concept to fabric sample in 2-4 weeks. Our Sample & Prototype Workshop develops, samples, and validates custom fabric constructions. Start your prototype project today.`,
};
---

<Layout metadata={metadata} breadcrumbs={crumbs}>
  <section class="px-6 sm:px-6 py-16 sm:py-20 mx-auto max-w-5xl">
    <a href="/randdcenter" class="text-sm text-gray-500 hover:underline">&larr; Back to R&D Center</a>
    <div class="mt-4 grid md:grid-cols-5 gap-10">
      <div class="md:col-span-3">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-primary uppercase tracking-wider">Lab 05</p>
        <h1 class="mt-2 text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold">Fabric Sample & Prototype Workshop</h1>
        <p class="mt-3 text-lg text-muted">From engineering design to finished fabric — sampled, finished, and validated</p>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-2">
        <img
          src="/images/seekingtex/factory/fabric-sample-workshop.webp"
          alt="Seekingtex fabric sample and prototype workshop"
          class="w-full h-48 object-cover rounded-xl"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="px-6 sm:px-6 pb-12 mx-auto max-w-4xl prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert">
    <h2>Where design becomes fabric</h2>
    <p>
      A fabric specification, no matter how detailed, cannot reveal how the material will actually perform until it is
      woven, finished, and tested. That is why our Fabric Sample & Prototype Workshop is designed to translate engineering
      data into physical fabric samples as quickly and accurately as possible. Every new {SITE.name} fabric construction — and every
      significant custom development — passes through this workshop before production tooling is committed.
    </p>
    <p>
      The workshop is fully equipped for simultaneous sampling of woven, knitted, and non-woven constructions with
      various coating and finishing options. This parallel-workflow approach cuts prototype lead time to 2-4 weeks from
      engineering release, compared to the industry norm of 6-8 weeks. When your application demands a specialized
      solution, we can move from concept to finished sample in under a month.
    </p>

    <h2>Workshop capabilities</h2>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Workstation</th><th>Equipment</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr
          ><td>Weaving</td><td
            >Sample rapier loom (190 cm width), Dobby shedding, up to 12 harness frames</td
          ><td>Small-scale woven fabric production for sampling and prototyping</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Knitting</td><td>Circular knitting machine (up to 36 gauge), flatbed knitting machine</td><td
            >Sample knit fabric production for performance and comfort textiles</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Coating & lamination</td><td
            >Knife-over-roll coater, thermal laminator, gravure coater</td
          ><td>Application of PU, acrylic, silicone, and other functional coatings</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Finishing range</td><td
            >Lab padder, drying oven, curing chamber, calendering unit</td
          ><td>Application of DWR, antimicrobial, UV absorber, and other chemical finishes</td></tr
        >
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>The prototype journey — step by step</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Engineering handover</strong> — The design package (fabric construction spec, FEA report, bill of materials, finishing recipe)
        is formally reviewed by the workshop lead and the project engineer. Any manufacturing concerns are flagged and resolved
        before sampling begins.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Fabric production</strong> — The fabric is produced according to the engineering specification. For woven: the
        weave pattern is loaded from the CAD system. For knitted: the stitch structure is programmed. For non-woven: the web
        formation parameters are set.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Finishing & coating</strong> — The greige fabric is processed through the finishing range. Coatings are applied
        using the specified method and cured under controlled conditions.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Performance testing</strong> — Samples are cut and sent to the Textile Performance Testing Lab for evaluation.
        Results are compared against the target specification.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Prototype review</strong> — A formal sign-off meeting is held with engineering, production, and quality teams.
        Any required design changes are documented and incorporated into the final specification.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <div class="not-prose my-10 p-6 rounded-xl bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900 border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 mb-3 uppercase tracking-wider">
        Sampling Timeline — Typical Fabric Prototype Schedule
      </p>
      <div class="space-y-2 text-sm">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 p-2 rounded bg-white dark:bg-gray-950">
          <span class="w-12 text-xs font-bold text-blue-600">5 d</span><span class="flex-1"
            >Engineering review — construction spec finalized, materials ordered</span
          >
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 p-2 rounded bg-white dark:bg-gray-950">
          <span class="w-12 text-xs font-bold text-blue-600">5 d</span><span class="flex-1"
            >Weaving/knitting — fabric produced on sample machinery</span
          >
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 p-2 rounded bg-white dark:bg-gray-950">
          <span class="w-12 text-xs font-bold text-blue-600">3 d</span><span class="flex-1"
            >Finishing — scouring, heat-setting, coating, curing</span
          >
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 p-2 rounded bg-white dark:bg-gray-950">
          <span class="w-12 text-xs font-bold text-blue-600">5 d</span><span class="flex-1"
            >Performance testing — UPF, waterproof, breathability, tensile, abrasion</span
          >
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 p-2 rounded bg-white dark:bg-gray-950">
          <span class="w-12 text-xs font-bold text-blue-600">2 d</span><span class="flex-1"
            >Prototype review — results evaluated, spec adjusted if needed, sign-off</span
          >
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 p-2 rounded bg-white dark:bg-gray-950">
          <span class="w-12 text-xs font-bold text-blue-600">20 d</span><span class="flex-1"
            >Total lead time: concept to finished prototype sample</span
          >
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Custom sampling for unique applications</h2>
    <p>
      The Sample & Prototype Workshop is where we solve the problems that standard fabric constructions cannot address. Recent
      examples include:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        A high-stretch knit fabric for compression sportswear, requiring a custom spandex feed ratio and finishing
        process to achieve the target 30 % stretch with 95 % recovery.
      </li>
      <li>
        A lightweight waterproof/breathable woven fabric for outdoor jackets, with a microporous PU coating developed
        to achieve 5000 mm waterproofness and 5000 g/m&sup2;/24h MVTR simultaneously.
      </li>
      <li>
        An eco-friendly fabric made from recycled polyester with a PFC-free DWR finish, where the prototype was used to
        validate performance before the client committed to a full production run.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Our sampling team</h2>
    <p>
      The workshop is staffed by six multi-skilled textile technicians, each cross-trained in at least two core
      disciplines (weaving, knitting, coating, finishing). The team lead is a master textile technologist with 16 years of experience spanning
      custom sampling to full production runs. Every prototype is assigned a dedicated project engineer who serves as
      the single point of contact for the client throughout the development process.
    </p>

    <h2>Client involvement</h2>
    <p>
      We actively encourage our clients to review key milestones during the prototype development — particularly the initial
      greige fabric inspection and the finished sample evaluation. Your feedback during these stages is invaluable in fine-tuning the
      fabric before it enters production. We do not sample in a vacuum; we sample in partnership with you.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="px-6 sm:px-6 pb-20 mx-auto max-w-4xl text-center">
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900 p-8">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Start your fabric prototype project</h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-muted">
        Tell us about the fabric you need and we will propose a prototype development plan.
      </p>
      <a
        href="/contact"
        class="mt-4 inline-block px-6 py-3 bg-primary text-white font-semibold rounded-md hover:bg-primary/90"
        >Contact our sampling team</a
      >
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
